{"id":"0711.3601","submitter":"Sijme-Jan Paardekooper","authors":"S.-J. Paardekooper, G. Mellema","title":"Growing and moving low-mass planets in non-isothermal disks","comments":"Accepted for publication in Astronomy and Astrophysics","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1051/0004-6361:20078592","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We study the interaction of a low-mass planet with a protoplanetary disk with\na realistic treatment of the energy balance by doing radiation-hydrodynamical\nsimulations. We look at accretion and migration rates and compare them to\nisothermal studies. We used a three-dimensional version of the hydrodynamical\nmethod RODEO, together with radiative transport in the flux-limited diffusion\napproach. The accretion rate, as well as the torque on the planet, depend\ncritically on the ability of the disk to cool efficiently. For densities\nappropriate to 5 AU in the solar nebula, the accretion rate drops by more than\nan order of magnitude compared to isothermal models, while at the same time the\ntorque on the planet is positive, indicating outward migration. It is necessary\nto lower the density by a factor of 2 to recover inward migration and more than\n2 orders of magnitude to recover the usual Type I migration. The torque appears\nto be proportional to the radial entropy gradient in the unperturbed disk.\nThese findings are critical for the survival of protoplanets, and they should\nultimately find their way into population synthesis models.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 22 Nov 2007 15:35:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-13"}
{"id":"0711.3602","submitter":"Nelson Pinto-Neto","authors":"Nelson Pinto-Neto and Bernardo M. O. Fraga","title":"Cosmic acceleration from interaction of ordinary fluids","comments":"10 pages, no figures, accepted for publication in General Relativity\n  and Gravitation","journal-ref":"Gen.Rel.Grav.40:1653-1662,2008","doi":"10.1007/s10714-007-0565-5","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":null,"abstract":"  Cosmological models with two interacting fluids, each satisfying the strong\nenergy condition, are studied in the framework of classical General Relativity.\nIf the interactions are phenomenologically described by a power law in the\nscale factor, the two initial interacting fluids can be equivalently\nsubstituted by two non interacting effective fluids, where one of them may\nviolate the strong energy condition and/or have negative energy density.\nAnalytical solutions of the Friedmann equations of this general setting are\nobtained and studied. One may have, depending on the scale where the\ninteraction becomes important, non singular universes with early accelerated\nphase, or singular models with transition from decelerated to accelerated\nexpansion at large scales. Among the first, there are bouncing models where\ncontraction is stopped by the interaction. In the second case, one obtains dark\nenergy expansion rates without dark energy, like $\\Lambda$CDM or phantomic\naccelerated expansions without cosmological constant or phantoms, respectively.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 22 Nov 2007 15:36:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
